textDisplay:
I've been a critical thinker and have been training the focus of my eyes in video games to track down even the smallest pixel.
Just to prepare myself for the future Full-Dive VR related games, since most of it will be focused on the human brain.

My sleep schedule changes up & varies to early sleeping and late sleeping.
If i'm feeling like a night owl, i would stay up as late as 7-8 AM and sleep all the way to 4-5 PM.

If i do not feel like a night owl, i would sleep as early as 8-9 PM and sleep all the way to 5-7 AM.
Given these amount of hours i had put in sleep, i would theoretically be the most efficient human subject in terms of quick thinking & high focus.

Now to clarify, i had dropped out of Highschool on my own decision, due to my already massive amount of stress & depression.. i was a really isolated child.
Dropped out of Highschool at age 15 years old because i didn't want to end up hurting anyone, even if i had a lot of hate for the bullies, i put kindness above all.

While i do not have college/university education like most of you all here.
I've been doing a lot of my research on logical things on the internet, you can find lots of useful information that can really twist the heads of even the most educated human.

Obviously i am no Einstein, but logical thinking has helped me a lot and many people around me online has admired me for my way of words.
When you work with logic & reason, you can get through most arguments & end up being on the neutral side most of the time, because even when you're mistaken, you are neutral.

Do not get me wrong, i actually do love studying despite my obvious laziness trait being apparent in my life.
Most of the time i use the internet for all of my researching, this helps me get a ton of knowledge that would be useful to me, more than what a school would provide me.

I'm thankful that i have a father who is supportive of whatever i want to do in life & with online opportunities being so available these days.
I am looking forward to diving into the industry of video games & maybe highly advanced companies made for for Full-Dive VR.

My goal as a player is to become the faster Full-Dive VR user alive in the future.
That is why i look towards extensive virtual training on the focus of my eyes.

Just the concept of Full-Dive VR tournament opportunities existing in the near future, with massive prize pools to be won & official virtual game currencies to be earned in video games made by governments & not some third-party (Crypto,Bitcoin,NFT) bullshit, having to be able to use those currencies in the real world one day casually like going to a cafe.

Paying for the meals using the currency you earned in the game which is endorsed by the government.
Think even non-gamer adults out there would love this.

I am looking forward to future rivals too.
My age is 24 years old, on every 3rd of January.. one year will be added to my life!

textDisplay: This reminds me of when I was in high school (early 2000s.) I never started feeling awake until around 10-11am. Our classes started at 7: 30am and ended at 2: 45pm. I usually didn't finish until 11pm.  I had to wake up at 6: 30 or 6: 45am to have enough time to try to wake up, eat, and get ready. It was awful.

textDisplay: I love how you put the short answer in the thumbnail ! And the very interesting in-depth explanation ! My school started at 8AM. But sometimes, because it was either on the schedule or because a teacher was absent, we started at 8:50 or even 9:40AM. No wonder why I felt so much better those days. I mean, at the end of my last school year, I slept 1 to 3 hours a night ! There's a day where I only slept for maybe 20 minutes. And once I didn't even sleep and had to go to school. I was falling asleep during the last school periods that day. And when I graduated, I basically slept for over 12 hours a day for the first 2 weeks or so. Now, I'm a 21 (soon 22) years old adult, and my sleeping schedule is basically a night owl. I would typically fall asleep in the early afternoon to wake up at around 9PM in general.

textDisplay: The issue here is that the majority of people who want to make these kinds of schedule changes are, of course, the students. Bowing to the wishes of the students can be a very slippery slope (give an inch, take a mile sort of thing) so schools are not quick to make sweeping changes solely based on student advocacy. What's needed is more informed adult representation on behalf of the students. Particularly within the school boards since teachers themselves don't have very much administrative power in most states. However, this requires parents and other adults to take a considerable interest in developmental psychology which is not always at the forefront of their minds especially when they recall how hardcore school was for them when they were students. Maybe I'm making some leaps in logic here, but as a teacher, these are some of the things that I see regarding the issue.
textOriginal: The issue here is that the majority of people who want to make these kinds of schedule changes are, of course, the students. Bowing to the wishes of the students can be a very slippery slope (give an inch, take a mile sort of thing) so schools are not quick to make sweeping changes solely based on student advocacy. What's needed is more informed adult representation on behalf of the students. Particularly within the school boards since teachers themselves don't have very much administrative power in most states. However, this requires parents and other adults to take a considerable interest in developmental psychology which is not always at the forefront of their minds especially when they recall how hardcore school was for them when they were students. Maybe I'm making some leaps in logic here, but as a teacher, these are some of the things that I see regarding the issue.

textDisplay:
Most of this video is just complete bullshit.

Circadian rhythms don't hold as much sway over your life as these sorts of videos make them out to. You are able to completely shift your circadian rhythm, teens can go to bed sooner, most are just unwilling because the first couple days of doing so are difficult and often school life doesn't allow for it. Things like sticking to a sleep schedule and adjusting lighting, exercise, diet, and caffeine can all help shift your circadian rhythm forward and back as needed. A consistent schedule and lighting are often all you need to do it. Your rhythm is almost completely based on what you need it to be. Every teen, given there's nothing else preventing them from going to sleep sooner (such as homework or insomnia) can go to bed sooner and can adapt to doing so without a problem.

The real problem is how schools cause teens to go to bed later and disrupt their sleep cycle to the point their rhythm ends up so out of wack as it becomes a struggle to maintain a working schedule. It steals development social time from students and replaces it with homework and extracurricular activities. Schools often fail to provide students time to actually develop socially with those around them, leaving the only times to do so being if you can somehow squeeze it in during class or ignore your homework or other activities after school. Often times after school is filled with too much homework or required extracurricular activities and are often paired with educationally inadequate familial situations (in terms of pressure, as most families fall to either side of putting the right amount of pressure on school work, giving far too much or too little). On top of no social time, it provides little time to explore interests and leisure activities. Most students are left to somehow find time outside of school, which they often already lack, to explore potential hobbies and interests (which they are also typically expected to know by the time they're 16-18).

Tying into this lack of time, even if teens manage to get their duties out of the way in time to go to bed at 10, an interesting phenomena often called Revenge Bedtime Procrastination sets in, where people will happily sacrifice sleep for leisure time they failed to properly get during the day. As students tend to have little of this time, I would assert that they are more likely to attempt to stay up later to gain more of this time back at the cost of sleep - even if they don't realize this is why they're doing it.

If anything, the end times are more of a problem than the start times, as end times being further back in the day would and does cause students to lose even more of these precious evening hours. The evening is a time when students can still participate in the working and social world and explore their hobbies out of the home on their own time, pushing school further back into this time limits further what they can do socially and what they can explore. Time in the morning can't make up for this as most places are still getting going - and you're proposing they sleep through this morning time and waste it anyway.

textDisplay: 6:00 - I might be wrong but I’m pretty sure that is my school! I live in Edina, MN, a first ring suburb of Minneapolis and currently am a junior in HS. When I was at one of the 2 middle schools, we switched from a 7:25 start and 2:35 end in 7th grade to a 9:20 start and 4:05 end in 8th. Then once I got to the high school we have started at 8:30 and ended at 3:16 every day. Since it’s a public school and we need buses to have separate times for elementary, middle, and high school that has been flipped around for each age of kids. Not sure exactly the times but the 6 elementary schools all start at ~7:30 and end ~2:30, the 2 middle schools are 9:20-4:05, and the high school is 8:30-3:16. I think it’s a perfect schedule as I am busy after school with golf and lots of AP classes so I can sleep 11-7 every night.

Since it’s a public school and we need buses to have separate times for elementary, middle, and high school that has been flipped around for each age of kids. Not sure exactly the times but the 6 elementary schools all start at ~7:30 and end ~2:30, the 2 middle schools are 9:20-4:05, and the high school is 8:30-3:16. I think it’s a perfect schedule as I am busy after school with golf and lots of AP classes so I can sleep 11-7 every night.

textDisplay: By the time I was done with school I was in such a horrible, self harming state, and I had been like that for years. For so long infact that I didn't even know I was legitimately depressed. I would have mental breakdowns on a daily basis, beating myself up in fits of anger at home and bursting into tears at the counselors office. It was horrible, I am so glad to never have to see the 4 walls of the tiny classroom I was holed up in every day for 2 years ever again. It brought me to the worst mental state that I'd ever been in. The "help" they provided only made it worse, sending people to my home every few weeks at random to check up on me, the day I got my birthday present I was screaming and shouting at the top of my lungs in happiness because my Girlfriend got me a new graphics card. They were waiting outside knocking and they thought I had a mental episode. They didn't believe that I was genuinely just happy and so I was sent into a youth therapy program where I was forced to talk to people I didn't know about every little detail of my life. And while I still wasn't well in the head I had to lie and pretend that I was slowly recovering and getting better when in fact, being forced to go to therapy was just another unnecessary stress that lead me into some emotional episodes and fits of self harm. It is disgusting that the current state of schooling is at all considered acceptable and I hope my story sheds some light on the fact that change is necessary for the sake of all the other kids in the same situation I was in. It'll be okay, I want everyone in my situation to know that it will be okay in the end. As hard as it can be to see in those times of stress and anxiety, better days are to come and you shouldn't let school be too big a burden on your childhood. I attempted suicide multiple times as a kid and I'm an idiot for doing so. There's a lot more to life and it's truly, deeply disgusting that for many, the first 18 years are nothing but torture on a daily basis. Stay well, keep your head up and focus on the bigger picture.

textDisplay: ): my college classes are 2.5-5 hrs long and we start at 8 am. we get 15 min breaks during the 2.5 class and a 30 min break during the 5 hr class, which is insane. I have ADHD and a few months after I began at my uni, I began to get chronically exhausted and stressed and have developed a tic disorder that really impacts my functionality even more. My school runs on a quarterly system, with 10 weeks equaling a quarter, and our materials are so intensive that every single student is stressed, exhausted, depressed, anxious, etc. I am not the only person w ADHD that has developed the same things from being at this Uni, which I find really disgusting that regardless of the major health impact these classes have had on us, the University only cares about money. The worst part is that once you start at this university, you can't leave because credits do not transfer, and what makes that even worse, is that the school does not make that a public notice before beginning there. It's a complete shock when you get there how incredibly rigorous and exhausting it is and then after about a year of studies, you finally find out that you cannot leave unless you want to start over again. So sad and we all tried to justify the actions, however, once COVID hit, the school would not lower tuition even though we were not using the utilities we were paying for, and with that, I believe everyone saw how much of a scam our University is. The worst part is that we are the most successful and famous art school in the world, as we have campuses in Europe and one that recently closed down in China. Parents send their kids to study here and so many high schoolers say that it's their dream school. The part that makes me the most frustrated is how some of our professors will literally shorten our deadlines a few days before a presentation because "sleep is important," so instead they want us to stay up all night for days straight to then turn in a project 6 hrs earlier because they believe it'll help when in reality, I know all students will agree that, NO IT DOES NOT. Then when we try to speak up, they love to say, "Welcome to reality," as if that's a real reality. It is not and that has been PROVEN by every alumni who have said that our school could care less about us and that the workplace post-graduation is so much better and bosses are so much more understanding and helpful. Just to give yall a reference, our projects are full-on interior architectural projects that would be completed by an entire team within 1yr, however, we only get 10 weeks and we do it individually. Just think about that.

textDisplay: It doesnt stop at high school. College isnt necessarily set up in the best way either. And the more you learn in college, the more you realize capitalism is the root of all these issues. overloading on classes, doing ECs and having leadership roles, finding an internship, while balancing health and a social life is basically impossible. Taking things easy needs to be normalized IN GENERAL in the academic world. College kids always complain about being tired but also at a certain point, especially seniors, we will stop giving a shit about getting good grades at the compromise of less sleep. I'm about to graduate college and gosh do I feel mentally numb and burnt out, and it only took me 3.5 years of college to actually realize what I want to do as a career.

textDisplay:
my shcool is an hour (by bus) away, and starts at 8. Which means i have to wake up at 6 so that i have time to do everything i need to, take the bus at 7, be at school from 8am-3pm, and then an hour bus back, and im home around 4:15 pm. Now by this time im too tired and worn out to do any of my hobbies, so i end up just sitting the rest of the time at home, and then try go to sleep at 9. Its a vicious cycle. Now thankfully we dont have homework, but our assignments can b pretty big sometimes. I used to be very active and healthy when i went to school near me, and now im at my most unhealthy and not active state. I've been complaining about exactly this for the 2 years ive been going to this school, and im just so tired.

On mondays i go to school 2 hours later (starting 9:50, bc i dont have spanish class), so bus at 8:40 but i choose to wake up at 7:20 ish. Waking up an hour later CHANGES SO MUCH. Im much more alive and present on mondays. An hour of sleep/waking up an hour later changes so much! Some of my other friends also started going to school at this time on mondays and they can also tell a huge difference.

Also: on thursdays we end school 4 school hours early, around 11:20, bc teachers do some meeting stuff idk. They could 100% just put at least one of these hours in the beginning of the day of 4 separate days. Id appreciate that much more than going home early quite honestly.

textDisplay: look im sure there are a lot of flaws with school but going to bed late and being tired is 100% our fault. It literally takes not even a week to get used to a new sleep schedule. If you want to stay up late that is 100% your fault and your problem. Not the schools. On a different conversation... i think that phones and computers make us stay up later because before phones you just didnt have anything to do after dinner so you naturally went to sleep cause u were bored. Nowadays there is a lot to do at any time of the day. Thats the problem. Not schools. Im a student, i hate school like everyone else does, but blaming the schools for this is beyond me.

textDisplay: Humans are naturally curious and get interested in certain things, then learn more about them. You know how we saw things as a little kid and asked our parents about the thing? People care alot about you and if you don’t think so then I do.
Have a good day/night :)

textDisplay: School isn't even for students to learn, it's about exploiting the students. Parents have to go to work and can't look after their kids 24/7 and there comes the school in play. 5-8 hours of bombarding kids with mostly useless information they won't ever use in their life and "learning" subjects they are not interested in. The highschool I go to is considered the best highschool in my city, when applying for the school the principle said they keep the students stress free, they always keep them engaged and give them valuable life experience and knowledge. None of it is true. It is not stress free, especially when kids get bombarded with constant exams, quizzes and tests and on top of that most kids are pressured by their parents to study and get good grades. They keep the students engaged? Extremely rarely, only 2 teachers I have had do that, all the others are monotone, uninterested and give lectures for the sake of passing time so they can get their paycheck. The only form of life experience you get is valuable friendships, 99% of the "knowledge" you acquired you will either forget in a week or will never need in your life.

textDisplay: I never had an issue with my biological clock adjusting to early times. Been used to it as a kid as I had to share a room with my older sis (she was in middle school while I was in elementary) so it didn't affect me until later in highschool. Anyways flashforward to Sophomore/Upperclassman years of high school and new ED yay, ty cruel South Asians (now I don't worry about my weight with whatever I eat and I look good-- in your faces nasty aunties). Now with lacking nutrients and less sleep cuz there's strict deadlines, I would doze off many times. I fell asleep for 10 min in my senior year and my teacher was super concerned. I'm enjoying college alot more as my classes yes are in the morning and I wake up the same time as the school system, I feel fresh having less pressure. 3 hours of class per day is better than 8 hours.  I have more time for assignments through the day and can sleep enough at night, not needing full nighters. I think I'm learning and processing information better with more sleep and less time in classes.

textDisplay: As a student, I can confirm school is destroying my brain. Many of us students are forced upon unrealistic expectations as young kids.  These expectations put a stupid amount of stress on us, from constant note taking and listening to lectures to studying for tests and homework. We pretty much have no free time.

These expectations put a stupid amount of stress on us, from constant note taking and listening to lectures to studying for tests and homework. We pretty much have no free time.

textDisplay:
When it came to exams and important school projects that needed studying, whenever we mentioned that we don't have enough time for it, the first thought, always, was to shorten your sleep time. It was like it's a crime for you to SLEEP when you got exams. I did and still kinda do always feel guilty for any sleep I get I feel like I'm missing on sth or I'm wasting my time and if I have the time to sleep, I surely have the time to study.

I've grown and I'm out of school thankfully, but now I'm really realising that what they mostly did to us in the schools, was not that far off from literal torture.

textDisplay: How long i usually sleep is 6-8hours, but school has screwed me up. Last night, I've only slept less than 2 hours, like, idk, 1 hour and 20-30mins is my guess. I was busy studying for a test cause I felt so stressed with the amount of work I had, when I've finished 1 exam, there's always more exams to study and memorize in the next couple days for and that loop just continues on and on all the time, I even had a stronger anxiety attack due to this exact reason while trying to study for that test and I've been feeling anxious and stressed these days, the stress of how little time I have and how many tests there are and much work there is to be done, even today I have a presentation and another short test due tomorrow so I'm kind of restless and I studied that late also because last friday, 4 days ago, when I came home and decided to take a small nap, I woke up at midnight, it seems that I slept for 8 hours. Holy shit. Well, after being 5 hours of being awake, i fell asleep again for 6 hours, and then the next night I was oversleeping 9 hours after that and I felt sleepy even when I tried to study even after those many hours of sleep I've had so i kind of took my time with it. On top of that, there are countless of days where I sleep only 3-4 hours at schooldays and when it's holiday, no matter when i go to sleep, I always wake up at 10-12 am, probably cause I've been worked up with school. I usually have woken up at 6 and went to sleep somewhere near midnight, but never do i normally wake up at the middle of the day or sleep that much..it's frustrating.

We could show them studies from other schools in Sweden that start at 10 or 11 am that they perform better than our schools in the U.S. We could show them that schools that don't assign homework after class often perform better on tests than schools that do. Andddd nothing would happen. 

As a whole, the U.S's school system is outdated & was designed to benefit the industrial revolution. America loved the idea of the constitution saying how it's a 'living' document so it could evolve & develop with the country, but here we are not adapting to better suit the current generations & future generations of kids or even the adults.

textDisplay: It saddens me that the mental health of the students is not taken into consideration in school. In high-school I developed debilitating social anxiety and every day I went to class shaking, sweating and hyperventilating. I would have multiple panic attacks every single day but I never told anyone because I knew that they wouldn't understand and even if they did they couldn't do anything about it. As a result I went to school terrified for years, wasn't able to focus at all because of anxiety, my self esteem crashed and burned, I developed severe depression, and my academic performance was very poor.

textDisplay: I used to enjoy school  back in junior years. Soon after being in senior, I was just disappointed and angry because of how school fooled us. Before moving senior, they told us, we can choose our strand and courses to gain momentum and foundation before college. As excited as I am, I enrolled myself only to find out I'll be answering irrelevant and unrelated subjects to my chosen strand. They aren't just irrelevant, in fact, they are also taking up a lot of time than the prime subjects and in general, they are pretty useless for my career. Last year, I took business and accountancy, and my science teacher told me, "Bring plants and different types of rocks when you come to school. Thank you." I replied "For what ma'am?" She said "For output." And I firmly said No. I told her I enrolled for Business and Accountancy. I explained to her that in real world, entrepreneurs don't bring different rocks and plants when they run a business. Instead they bring money and assess the company's performance. She deactivated afterwards.

textDisplay:
Ive always had trouble sleeping.... from once I became a teen onwards. When I was really young I asked my parents if I could go to bed.
I've always been heavily sleep deprived and struggling to fall asleep since some time in highschool. I'm 28 now, heavily depressed, insomnia and trying to apply knowledge from what I learn online and the psychologist both at the same time doesn't work, because all I hear is two voices contradicting each other.

I'm pretty sure I am a night owl. I always naturally move my sleep rhythym up later and wake up later, too. Yet everyone keeps telling me I need to get up early because that is "normal". Yet when I do, even if I stick to it, which is very difficult, a 'normal' aka early bird sleep routine only makes me miserable.

textDisplay:
I also think the intense pressure put on your shoulders revolving around grades definitely hurts you because you either feel exhausted and pained after completing a hard assignment, or you feel like an absolute failure and get outrageously punished if you fail an assignment or class and parents claim you aren't trying hard enough, which hurts students a lot because maybe either the professor is bad at teaching, or no matter what the concepts are just too difficult to understand.
I'm in college and currently have a trigonometry professor named Altobelli (not sure if anyone has heard of him), but man he is seriously awful. People say all professors are good because they're doing their job but there's such a thing as bad professors.
I don't mind the concept of math, but when a professor explains it awfully no matter what help you get to solve it (which wastes so much time for your other classes), and gives you so much schoolwork and shows no sign of improving while failing so bad no matter how hard you try to the point where your parents are constantly ganging up on you with your grade? Yeah, this has DESTROYED my mental health and I really don't like math because of it. Not the concepts, but because of the horrible professors they hire. You're also determined to stay up really late to study hard so you understand the exam concepts and get a better grade.

textDisplay: People thinking that this is an excuse for staying up late or using technology before they sleep should check their facts. Yes, using technology or video games may not make your brain dumber and might actually improve it (depending on what you do/play) but if you use it before you sleep not only would it take you longer to sleep (due to the release of dopamine in your body) but it would also make you stay up later in general. Technology and video games are meant to be addicting and that's why you should limit your usage of them.

textDisplay:
This is exactly what I thought until I had to wake up at 06:00 for 5 consecutive days to get in time for the exams.
In that period I could easily fall asleep at 20:00 and force myself to wake up at a certain time on the morning with alarm. This was very different from my "usual" sleeping schedule as I used to sleep after 23:00 (if I tried anytime earlier I would just waste time on my bed)
and get up around 09:00.
This let me to believe that no one is a true night or day person, your sleeping schedule can be adjusted.
At the moment I can fall asleep at 21:00 and wake up naturally at 06:00.
I'm a 21 year old university student.

textDisplay:
The biggest problem I had with school was competition. The system is designed to compare students to one another in an environment where everyone is intellectually different. I assume governments approve of this method to "improve" the results of kids who are struggling, but really all it does is ruin their mental health and make it LESS likely to get better because of motivational issues, etc.

In Australia, the reason why I preach vocational tertiary education is because instead of failing/passing, there is a competency system where you can redo assessments and only you can see the results (not all but most courses). Did I mention there is no ranking system as well? So far it's helped me ease the tension of competing with other students and working at my own pace without stressing whether I'll get a low score or not is a breath of fresh air.

textDisplay:
I don't have a problem with anybody liking nor disliking school, but school is actually making you think so hard that your brain...... ACTUALLY HURTS! Like I'm not even joking when I said that. AND I'M SERIOUS! I got the reward for being the best student in my math class one time, but the thing is, I barely even tried. Out of my first 8 grades (K - 7), I only found one student of the many that enjoyed school because of the education. The rest either liked school because of friends, or didn't even like it at all. So I'd say there was an average of 28 students for each grade I was in, so let me do the math real quick...

Edit: Well see, I was encouraged to do a mathematical equation, but it already made me dumb. I had the idea in my head, but now I can't think of how to do it. I believe I have to multiply 8 (for the grades I've been in) with 28 (average students) to find out an estimated student count in my lifetime from K - 7, minus one because only one student said they liked school because of the education factor, then divide that by 224 , but my result is: 0.9955, in other words, 99.55% of students do not care about the education. So that's proof already.

Another example of people hating school is the fact that so much talking happens during class (with the exception of answering a question or asking a question). There's a reason that happens. People would rather talk about something that they find interesting than irrelevant to them. If school was really that interesting, everyone would be like "Wow! Remember Pi = 3.14?" I wish I could eat that number!"

School's lessons are just 99.9999999999% filler. Don't get me wrong, there is very few things that are actually useful, especially in math, but I'll go over these subjects individually later, but for now, look at how many lessons you probably forgot about by now. Forgetting something shows you that you don't care about something for the most part. That applies to almost everything. That's proof all of those lessons you've forgotten are useless information to you.

Math is the best subject but it is awful still (this is my opinion). At least you need math for a lot of things in real life, and it can be kinda fun because it's sometimes kinda like puzzle solving. (Key word: CAN).

Reading (ELA) is just boring. There's so many things you could do that is not reading a book. Learning vocabulary words, well you have the internet in 2021.

Science is just for people that want to study to become a Scientist. Let's be real here. The only time you really talk about science anywhere is if you wanna talk about the basic stuff. Those advanced crap are rarely talked about.

I don't even wanna talk about the next one. But I have to. History! Come on. You're going into the FREAKING FUTURE! NOT THE PAST! What? Can we time travel? YOU'RE OUTTA YOUR MIND? Like dang... I mean I guess it is cool and all to know your history... but... REALLY? WHY IS IT EVEN A MANDATORY SUBJECT TO BEGIN WITH? AND WHY, JUST WHY, ARE YOU FORCED TO LEARN HISTORY? THERE'S NO LOGIC IN THAT.

textDisplay:
I'm probably one of the few adults that completely agree with this.

The main question remains, how to convince a large group of adults suffering school induced brain damage? It's a self perpetuating problem. Teens are forced out of bed early, get brain damage, become adults, then force their own child's out of bed early because they think it's normal. If a schools objective was to develop a child's brain and educate them, then why do they start at the same hour most factory workers do?

As a software engineer I try to start my workdays at 9 am, unless I feel tired then I come in late ( up to 11 am). No use in showing up to work early when tired and unproductive. If my boss doesn't like me starting this late, then he's free to replace me...

textDisplay:
School genuinely made me feel like an office worker, doing grunt work every single day...But it used to be different back then. I was actually having fun learning new things believe it or not. I was filled with excitement and thrill of learning new things, test my knowledge, get good grades, etc. I felt so good about it when I was younger and didn't care much about getting early. It feels sorrowful in a way whenever I have to look back at these memories...



Now I am demotivated, unhappy, sucked of all energy and interest, my creativity and way of expression totally crushed under the boulder of school educating system, which is even more apparent during online school. While I liked it for the fact that it inspired me to follow my art passions of drawing, animating, writing, game and web developing; I didn't like it for the fact that it gives me practically no time to practice these things. You honestly won't believe how much pain it is to wake up in the morning, telling to yourself "Alright today I am going to practice drawing and other stuff" only to realize you've been wasting your entire time studying and having no time to do all those things because of how fast time flies by. Heck it's not even guaranteed that the things you learn in online school will be remembered. And that's what made me demotivated...







Honestly I have been ranting about online school being detrimental to my psyche and cognitive functions like a little baby but it's true. Online learning makes you feel like a zombie more than anything. You just sit here starring blankly in the screen, listening to a disembodied voice of a teacher explaining yet another lesson in the most boring way imaginable while throwing a barrage of homework at you. I had a conversation with my mother where she was concerned about my well-being when it came to learning, always asking where is the motivation I had and how I was sinking down (my grades aren't really bad, but she was concerned because I didn't participate enough in class.). I tried explaining to her the reason but she denied it claiming that last year I did online school yet I was actively participating in class so I didn't have any excuse to act the way I am now in this year's online school. That honestly felt like a big punch in the heart because she was the only one who would support me and understood my feelings better than any other. And now she turned her back on me....OK maybe I am overexaggerating about that but still, it felt so wrong that the only person I could trust was dismissing my feelings.



I still don't plan to give up on school entirely but if thus continues like this, I might have no choice but to drop out just because of how stressful it has become. Sorry for making this really long. I probably wasted your valuable time with you having to read through my useless ranting. But if you managed to get this far, thank you for your patience. I really hope you felt the same way I did.
textOriginal:
School genuinely made me feel like an office worker, doing grunt work every single day...But it used to be different back then. I was actually having fun learning new things believe it or not. I was filled with excitement and thrill of learning new things, test my knowledge, get good grades, etc. I felt so good about it when I was younger and didn't care much about getting early. It feels sorrowful in a way whenever I have to look back at these memories...



Now I am demotivated, unhappy, sucked of all energy and interest, my creativity and way of expression totally crushed under the boulder of  school educating system, which is even more apparent during online school. While I liked it for the fact that it inspired me to follow my art passions of drawing, animating, writing, game and web developing; I didn't like it for the fact that it gives me practically no time to practice these things. You honestly won't believe how much pain it is to wake up in the morning, telling to yourself "Alright today I am going to practice drawing and other stuff" only to realize you've been wasting your entire time studying and having no time to do all those things because of how fast time flies by. Heck it's not even guaranteed that the things you learn in online school will be remembered. And that's what made me demotivated...







Honestly I have been ranting about online school being detrimental to my psyche and cognitive functions like a little baby but it's true. Online learning makes you feel like a zombie more than anything. You just sit here starring blankly in the screen, listening to a disembodied voice of a teacher explaining yet another lesson in the most boring way imaginable while throwing a barrage of homework at you. I had a conversation with my mother where she was concerned about my well-being when it came to learning, always asking where is the motivation I had and how I was sinking down (my grades aren't really bad, but she was concerned because I didn't  participate enough in class.). I tried explaining to her the reason but she denied it claiming that last year I did online school yet I was actively participating in class so I didn't have any excuse to act the way I am now in this year's online school. That honestly felt like a big punch in the heart because she was the only one who would support me and understood my feelings better than any other. And now she turned her back on me....OK maybe I am overexaggerating about that but still, it felt so wrong that the only person I could trust was dismissing my feelings.



I still don't plan to give up on school entirely but if thus continues like this, I might have no choice but to drop out just because of how stressful it has become. Sorry for making this really long. I probably wasted your valuable time with you having to read through my useless ranting. But if you managed to get this far, thank you for your patience. I really hope you felt the same way I did.

textDisplay:
My school used start at 7:30 am, but because it annoyed me so much I decided to miss 2 classes and come to school everyday at 9:40 am.
At first my friends questioned it and I just told them, I barely cared about school if they didnt care about our mental health. It kept going like this for 2 weeks and some teachers got so sick of it, and a few teachers agreed. Til one day the principle pulled me into her office and asked why this was happening and if everything was Ok at home.
I simply tell her that the school started too early for my functioning. She said it was no excuse and it's school policy to arrive on time. I leave the office saying "This talk we had won't change the time I arrive", and I kept arriving at 9:40 am. Until the school makes a new rule talking about mental health and how they decided to change the arrival time to 9:55 am.

It was so funny to me how they pretended they cared about our mental health and happiness, but their only excuse was that it was "school policy".

And yet I feel so smart doing Mathematics to solve situations even using algebra.... Geography, my favourite subject, I feel so good when i can identify rocks and the way volcanoes work along with natural features...Being able to speak properly because of learning English, I'm a Caribbean person and if i speak to an american in my creole they'll understand absolutely NOTHING... and yet i can use clothing and textiles to mend my ripped clothes and to make clothes...and yet i can use food and nutrition to learn about the dietary needs and managing families, and yet i can use English literature to understand poems and novels and to write them being able to express myself in a poetic good sounding way.... and yet i can use i.t to learn advanced things about computers and yet i can use the many different things learned in school throughout my life whether its my career field or not.....AND YET THIS CHANNEL TEACHES SCIENCE WHICH IS ALSO TAUGHT IN SCHOOL so are you destroying our brains then?
Yes, school can be hectic at times where i myself also stay up late some nights to do work and wake up quite early, sometimes stessed myself. But think about it....does anything in life come easy?If our bodies got accustomed to sleeping late cant it get accustom to sleeping earlier too? A little tip: go to bed around 7pm get up around 9pm, to do work or study go back to bed around 11pm, 12am for the latest and wake up 6am according to the time you have to wake up for school. thats actually 10 hours of sleep there and if you think 7 is to early go to bed 8pm for the latest. Thats what i do, ( most days) You need to work! You need to make sacrifices! You watch those motivational videos all the time about hard work and pushing on but yet you learn nothing from it. Let me tell you, NOTHING COMES EASY IN LIFE. Some teachers actually over-do it with homework Cough especially spanish teachers cough,cough but still, its there for practice and to make sure you understand. Tests are there to see how much you learned even though they love shaming people for bad grades but if you pay attention in class trying to LEARN what the teacher is explaining, thats less study time. Dont even think about saying ,'oh well my parents could have taught me to read or to write or about the earth or about cooking or about managing families or about etc.' Dont even think about saying' oh well i could learn it from youtube or from google or etc.' Because if you dont know what photesynthesis is, how do you know to search for it to learn it how do you know do search for Pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis? How do you know to search for ecosystems or hemming or lasagna? Hard work brings rewards!

SHAME ON YOU ASAPSCIENCE giving people more reasons to hate school, a place where we can learn things we never knew. :| Oh whats that i sound like a nerd? Oh thank you i appreciate the compliment:)

Thats what i do, ( most days) You need to work! You need to make sacrifices! You watch those motivational videos all the time about hard work and pushing on but yet you learn nothing from it. Let me tell you, NOTHING COMES EASY IN LIFE. Some teachers actually over-do it with homework *Cough* especially spanish teachers *cough,cough* but still, its there for practice and to make sure you understand. Tests are there to see how much you learned even though they love shaming people for bad grades but if you pay attention in class trying to LEARN what the teacher is explaining, thats less study time. Dont even think about saying ,'oh well my parents could have taught me to read or to write or about the earth or about cooking or about managing families or about etc.' Dont even think about saying' oh well i could learn it from youtube or from google or etc.' Because if you dont know what photesynthesis is, how do you know to search for it to learn it how do you know do search for Pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis?  How do you know to search for ecosystems or hemming or lasagna? Hard work brings rewards!

textDisplay: my school actually has always started as what people consider 'later' for schools, at around 8:30-9, which i still think isn't late enough, they're clearly trying to stay below 9am as much as possible, simply because that's the usual start time for adult jobs. i have two main problems with that, for one, it's forcing teenagers into the habits of a standard boring 9-5 job, which they say is 'preparation' but really it's frustrating for a lot of people, myself included, because i don't plan on having a 9-5 job as my career, nor do many others, plus, as you've said, it's just destroying our brains. waking up earlier is something that will come with age so why do they need to implement it now while we're still developing? it's really harmful and in the long run it's making the teachers jobs harder, by ruining our brains. when we start so early our circadian rhythms will be all messed up and we don't have the time or energy to study or do homework. it's really messed up.

textDisplay:
Unfortunately for a lot of parents School is a day care they drop their kids off before they go to work, hence the insane early start times. Often this isn't the fault of the parent but their employer. Both school and work should start later in the day and end earlier. Jeff Bezos famously doesn't schedule any meetings until 10AM at the earliest because he enjoys puttering around the house. Even as adults on the weekends with no responsibilities, we often don't like to start our days later in the morning. Left to my own devices, as a night owl, my circadian rhythm has my peak wakefullness around 9PM.

I'm insanely worried about this as my oldest is about to start school. I think homeschooling would be an option but since like most parents I have to work full time, I don't have the time to home school. I do hope I can find a school that starts later in the day though. Maybe all it would take is telling a few parents that starting earlier is literally making their child less intelligent, more prone to substance abuse and other behavioral issues but I think there are too many parents who will think "Well I started early and I'm fine."

textDisplay:
Every day I have class starting at 7 AM, meaning I have to leave my house at 6 every day.
Then I spend the next 8 hours attending my regular classes, though right after my last class I start my 3-4 hours of daily extracurriculars.
When I'm finally done with my work at school, it's 7 PM (if there are no extra practices/rehearsals or performances), and it's time to take the hour trip back home.
Finally by 8 PM I'm home, and when I'm done eating it's 8:30. Now would be a great time to take a shower, relax a bit after a *12 hour school day*- but wait! I just remembered I have several hours of homework to complete and I still need to practice my instrument and study!
I finally climb into bed at, if I'm lucky, 1 AM, where I have my usual anxiety-ridden, short sleep knowing I have to get up the next morning at 5:40 AM to have knowledge crammed into my head under the bright classroom lights of my high school.
I admittedly am not taking many difficult classes this year, but next year, I know which classes I want to take and from what I've been told they give an absurd amount of homework.
Through the next few years of my highschool career, I will have nothing but work, work, work and very little sleep.
And adults wonder why teens these days are sufferings so much from stress and other mental illness.
These are not our golden years, these years are nothing but hell.

I know that unfortunately, many students may be able to relate to my little seminar, and to those people I wish the best of luck :) You are loved, please don't do anything to hurt yourself and make sure you talk to a friend when things get tough!

textDisplay:
The problem with humans and science is that nobody ever changes the way things are done until direct causal relationships have been old news for decades. Despite beginning to demonstrate this in the present, this knowledge won't salvage the statistical cohort that are most impacted by our worst practices paradigm.

No one with any real ability to challenge the way things are done is eager to upend anything—even in order to do less harm. I guess there is a whole lot of cognitive science to say that it will always tend to be that way. It makes me sad.

textDisplay:
My depression caused by sleep deprivation from middle school and tenth grade high school was at a tipping point when I was having suicidal thoughts. Then a school counselor suggested to my mother I transfer to a public charter school in our home city where their education methods were different: one subject for the whole month, and you can come into the open-room classroom between 8 to 4 anytime you see fit. I was able to get a LOT of needed sleep, enjoyed my education at my own pace, and discovered my love for creativity in art and story.

Then I went to the Art Institute of California 😣

textDisplay:
Honestly, school doesn't even start at that bad of a time. It's getting there and back. My high school started class at 7:45AM. That's not terrible. Meanwhile, the bus picked us up at 5:10AM and dropped us off at the campus at like 6:30AM. Yes, an hour+ BEFORE class. My stop was last after school, so I wouldn't even get home until like 4:30PM. School ended at 2:45PM.

Nevermind after school activities that would guarantee enough sleep was impossible. Walking to the stop took 30mins, so I was up at almost 4AM EVERY DAY. 4 hours BEFORE class. WHY?

textDisplay:
I feel like this video is missing the point with the connection between sleep, time and better performance. The answer for why kids stay up late and deprive themselves of sleep is actually extremely simple, it's because when you go to sleep the next day begins. And when the next day begins, you have to go to school again. Staying up an extra 2 hours instead of sleeping is 2 more hours you have to yourself to do what YOU want.

As an aside, you can also make the conclusion that smarter and more academically proficient students are managing their time, able to finish their work, and giving school the attention it's asking for. While on the other hand, students who aren't as proficient tend to let work pile up, disregard assignments, or develop a habit of apathy towards academics. School demands A LOT of your time (too much in my opinion) and students who stay up late are just trying to take some of it back. It's not intrinsically related to who gets more or less sleep in my opinion.

textDisplay: I have/had a photographic memory, but during my teens my sleep deprivation got so bad that nowadays I can't tell if I still have it or not, I used to be able to play back fully detailed "video" in my mind of things I'd seen, but now I only see a small glimpse for no longer than a second. It takes a whole lot more effort to recall things than it used to do. Only years after bad sleeping schedules and school stress did I see a video warning me of how it could destroy a photographic memory. textDisplay: school is such a cesspool of bad decisions and loss of focus on what public education is supposed to be, and it just keeps getting worse. It's not about the kids anymore, it's about money. When I was in elementary school, I had severe mental issues, particularly ADHD and anger. Even then, it took my mom fighting a war against the schoolboard to get me a supervisor and special programs and in a few years I was rehabilitated back into regular school. If my mom didn't fight so hard, I probably wouldn't have ever gotten better. Now, if a kid in my situation had a parent try to seek the same help in my city, it would be impossible, because of new rules and budget cuts and all that bullshit. If we really want to change the school system, we have to elect the right people in our areas who will actually properly fund shit. It all comes down to money.

textDisplay:
Hear hear, the Right Honourable Gentleman is very much correct on this important topic.

I personally find it almost frightening how much our alarm clock culture chooses to ignore sleep despite it being important enough to take roughly a third of our lives. One would imagine there has to be a good reason for that.

I'm just really glad that my country does take sleep quite seriously (or at least my schools did) and the earliest days in high school were 8.45 am (a 35 minute increase compared to secondary school). Combined with a brisk 30+ minute walk to school every morning, it really helped me to mentally get ready for classes, be more alert and just generally feel better. Though as a chronic night owl I still preferred the days that started even later. Usually more than 4 days off from school was enough for my sleep schedule to be pushed back by several hours, returning to 'normal' afterwards being the same pain it always is.

textDisplay: I think schooling needs to be rethought entirely. The average student probably goes on to utilize what, like 20% of what they spent time on in school? Think of how much more fulfilled kids would be if they had all of those thousands of hours as a kid to explore their passions and interests in an environment that helps mentor them and steer them toward productive uses of those interests? This rigid schooling structure is not backed by science, it was implemented many decades ago and never challenged in its validity. Schools could be something truly incredible with a little bit of innovation and investment, maybe they could simply be called learning centers because kids would have a lot of say in how they spend their time there.

textDisplay:
I know from personal experience how rough and stress inducing school can be.
Last school year, I probabilities averaged no more than 6 - 5 hours of sleep. This started having real side effects, since there would be classes I just couldn’t stay awake in. This year, things have gotten even worse. I would consider it a good day if I got though just 2 of my classes without falling asleep. I was still managing to get As, but a couple weeks ago, the stress really started ramping up that I couldn’t get a grip, cussing my grades to plummet. On top of this, I think I am suffering from burnout, but, I cannot properly respond to burnout since school has a strict schedule I need to follow. Anyway, actually just yesterday, I finally had enough, and practically had a mental break down. I decided that for the next couple of days, I just won’t go to school, since it was clearly doing more harm than good to me, and fortunately, I do have supportive parents that agree with my assessment.
I was reading through this comment section, and seeing similar stories, so I just want to let you all know that you are not alone. The school system needs to change, and if the adults ain’t gonna do it, then we should.

textDisplay:
25. Why is that number important. Because that is the age you are when your rational thinking skills and critical thinking skills are complete. Before then, teens and young people are really adept at high risk taking but the closer they get to 25, the less that becomes. Also their fast reflexes as well. I studied a bit about this in college at the age of 24, (pssst, I'm now in my 40's) already had 2 kids by that point. Our lecturer told us not to touch drugs, not to experiment with things that literally could damage our growing brains - erm too late for me I thought. A bit of 4/20 a few years before that and totally hugging the porcelain drunk. So what had I done to my brain?

My eldest child is now 20 years old and despite my warnings, she still went out, got totally hugging the porcelain drunk at 18, experimented with 4/20, no amount of me telling her what it was doing to her brain would stop her. Teens and young people are just natural risk takers. It's why car insurance is so high for this age group. They also sleep a tonne.

However I am also thinking of chronotypes as well. Wouldn't it be cool if we had a night school for all those beings who are still in their primitive brains of - human protect tribe whilst sleeping? What if we could model our lives around our natual chronotypes I'm a wolf - and our circadian rythms I'm a night owl. I'm more alert and focused at night. I perform better at night. It would be great if the 15% of us who are wolves, the 10% who are dolphins and I don't know how many percent who are night owls, can be out at night - working, attending college/universities or school. We can if there are enough people who would want to.

textDisplay:
Probably one of the reason why I attend for school is to talk to classmates for my mental sanity. Highschool has been a lot of work especially since I am one of the only 400 students out of 6000 who passed a state of the art Mathematics and Science based highschool in the City during my first year. I'm currently in 4th year. Whats worse is that at my very first day in this school, the first thing that the head announces after the Flag ceremony was that "Sleep does not exist in this school." Imagine hearing that with your hopes up in your first day after you were accepted by a state of the art highschool. And they were not kidding. Even with how many times I've adjusted my schedule, I still sleep later than intended and at times I don't even get sleep. Whats more frustrating is that even after the president said that homeworks shouldn't be given during weekends, THE SCHOOL GIVES STACKS OF HOMEWORK DUE ON MONDAY. the purpose of that rule was to let students have a personal life and spend time with family, BUT NO, the school finds ways to get around that. I like learning yes, I even educate myself, but school is supposed to feel like a second home, not a mental prison. My parents and grandparents are even complaining about excess school work becuz they want me to go biking on weekends, but I never do becuz of homework. I am at risk of diseases due to lack of sleep especially since I have a lot of health issues but I'm trying not to let that be an excuse. I can't even enjoy meal time since after class ends, homework is due from 1:00 pm to 5:00pm and some until 11:59 pm on the same day it was given. So now I also eat later than usual becuz I'm constantly pressured by all this school work.

And one more thing, especially for artists like me, is ART BLOCK

textDisplay:
A lot of adults tell their kids that “Your teenage years are the best years of your life.” When really you 1. Get next to no sleep almost every night 2. Have to move classes in a few minutes without being late (even if the class is across the school) 3. Are expected to act like an adult while being treated like a child 4. Have almost no time for yourself because of homework you get 5. Have to deal with other kids who tend to be way more judgmental around that age 6. Try to ignore all the stress from lack of sleep and schoolwork, etc. 7. Deal with your messed up Circadian Rhythm 8. Listen to people tell you over and over that you need to get up early because you’re always late for school 9. Are just always tired and stressed out because of your responsibilities and everything.

Teenage years are not the best of your life, I’d give so much to be able to go back to my younger age, it was much better then.

textDisplay: Though I'm not a teenager anymore. I know just how important sleep is. I have sleep apnea, and it was left undiagnosed for a long time. What should be a shock to no one, one day I eventually broke down and became very sick. I struggled to hold conversations, remember things not just long term but even from a few minutes ago. I couldn't remember a simple sequence or list of things ex: milk, eggs, bread, butter. I would remember maybe the milk and eggs on a good day. I was highly irritable, just the slightest things that you'd be able to shrug off would send me into an uncontrollable rage. You need sleep and if you don't get it, it will mess you up. If you suffer from insomnia please find a sleep doctor and get tested. Insomnia is always a symptom never a cause! Sleep apnea is a very common problem but so many of us never know we have it! Snoring is also a symptom of sleep apnea!

textDisplay:
Me: Neurodivergent (ASD + comorbid ADHD) natural night owl.

My sleeping time on sleep meds (with a self-enforced schedule): 2 AM - 3 AM (minimum 1 AM).
My sleeping time on sleep meds (but I take them when I actually feel like going to bed): 5 AM - 6 AM (maximum 10 AM).

My waking time on sleep meds: 10 AM - 11 AM (minimum 9 AM).
My waking time on sleep meds (but I take them when I actually feel like going to bed): 12 PM - 2 PM (maximum 6 PM).

Time needed for my ADHD meds (Vyvanse) to begin taking noticeable effect: 2 hours.

So, hypothetically: if school starts at 8 AM, the latest I should wake up is 6 AM. But, 6 AM just so happens to be around the same time I naturally feel like going to bed.

Yeah.
